          "pause": true,
          "displayType": "poster",
          "buttonOnMobile": false,
          "label": "<p>Which gene acts as the master switch for testis formation in the human embryo?</p>",
          "x": 30,
          "y": 30,
          "width": 40,
          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>Which gene acts as the master switch for testis formation in the human embryo?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>Anti-Müllerian hormone (AMH) gene</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>AMH is secreted by Sertoli cells after the testis has already formed. It causes Müllerian duct regression but does not initiate testis differentiation.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>SRY (Sex-determining Region Y) gene</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Correct. SRY on the Y chromosome is expressed around week 7 in the indifferent gonad and directs it to form a testis. Without SRY, the default pathway leads to ovarian development.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>SOX9 gene</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>SOX9 is activated downstream of SRY and is important for sustaining testis development, but SRY is the master switch that initiates the entire cascade.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>DAX1 gene</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>DAX1 actually opposes SRY function and supports ovarian development. It is an anti-testis factor, not the master switch for testis formation.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "The correct answer is the SRY gene. Expressed at week 7 on the Y chromosome, it directs the indifferent gonad to form a testis. Without SRY, ovarian development proceeds by default."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Well done! SRY on the Y chromosome is expressed at week 7 in the indifferent gonad, triggering testis formation. Without SRY, the gonad defaults to an ovary."
                }
              ],
              "behaviour": {
                "enableRetry": true,
                "enableSolutionsButton": true,
