          "pause": true,
          "displayType": "poster",
          "buttonOnMobile": false,
          "label": "<p>Which cells in the testis are responsible for synthesising testosterone?</p>",
          "x": 30,
          "y": 30,
          "width": 40,
          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>Which cells in the testis are responsible for synthesising testosterone?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>Sertoli cells</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Sertoli cells are the nursing cells of the seminiferous tubules. They nourish developing sperm and produce inhibin, not testosterone.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Spermatogonia</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Spermatogonia are the diploid germ cells that divide to eventually produce spermatozoa. They do not have an endocrine function.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Interstitial cells of Leydig</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Correct. Leydig cells in the interstitial tissue between seminiferous tubules synthesise testosterone from cholesterol, stimulated by luteinising hormone from the anterior pituitary.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Peritubular myoid cells</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Myoid cells provide structural support and rhythmic contraction around the seminiferous tubules to move sperm, but they do not produce testosterone.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "The interstitial cells of Leydig produce testosterone from cholesterol, stimulated by luteinising hormone (LH). This is distinct from Sertoli cells, which produce inhibin and support spermatogenesis."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Correct! Leydig cells synthesise testosterone from cholesterol under the control of LH. High local testosterone is essential for every stage of spermatogenesis."
                }
              ],
              "behaviour": {
                "enableRetry": true,
                "enableSolutionsButton": true,
                "enableCheckButton": true,
