          "pause": true,
          "displayType": "poster",
          "buttonOnMobile": false,
          "label": "<p>Which hormone is the most reliable laboratory marker for confirming menopause?</p>",
          "x": 30,
          "y": 30,
          "width": 40,
          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>Which hormone is the most reliable laboratory marker for confirming menopause?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>Oestradiol</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Oestradiol does fall at menopause, but its levels fluctuate widely during perimenopause, making it unreliable as a single diagnostic marker.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Follicle-stimulating hormone (FSH)</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Correct. FSH rises above 30 IU/L at menopause because depleted ovarian follicles can no longer produce enough oestrogen and inhibin to maintain negative feedback on the pituitary.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Progesterone</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Progesterone is low in menopause due to absent ovulation, but it is also low during anovulatory cycles in premenopausal women, limiting its diagnostic value.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Luteinising hormone (LH)</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>LH does rise at menopause, but its elevation is less consistent and less pronounced than the FSH rise, making FSH the preferred confirmatory marker.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "FSH is the most reliable marker. At menopause, depleted follicles produce insufficient oestrogen and inhibin to suppress the pituitary, so FSH rises above 30 IU/L."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Correct! FSH above 30 IU/L is the most reliable hormonal marker of menopause, reflecting the loss of ovarian negative feedback from depleted follicles."
                }
              ],
              "behaviour": {
                "enableRetry": true,
                "enableSolutionsButton": true,
                "enableCheckButton": true,
